Introduction

The capacity to communicate across distance has expanded significantly, yet the experience of shared physical presence remains difficult to replicate. While messaging and video calls enable efficient exchange, they often fail to convey the feeling of another person’s presence within one’s physical space. This challenge lies at the core of Connected Environments, which explores how digital systems and IoT technologies can bridge people and places.

This project was developed within the Connected Environments Group Prototype and Pitch, focusing on communicating presence through non-screen-based interaction. Ishii and Ullmer’s concept of Tangible Bits provides a key foundation, demonstrating how digital information can be embedded in physical artefacts to support embodied interaction (Ishii & Ullmer, 1997). In addition, the project draws on animistic design principles, using lifelike motion to evoke the presence of another person.

This project, Butterfly Effect, proposes a networked interactive installation that transforms human presence into a tangible physical signal.

The Problem

How can presence be made tangible across distance?

Concept

The Butterfly Effect Installation is inspired by the butterfly effect metaphor, where small actions can produce significant outcomes in interconnected systems (Lorenz, 1963). This idea is translated into interaction design.

Two installations are placed in separate locations, each consisting of multiple butterfly devices. Every butterfly is paired with a counterpart in the remote location. When a person moves past one installation, both paired butterflies respond simultaneously through wing movement.

In addition to immediate response, rotation is used to represent accumulated presence over time. If multiple butterflies are rotated in different directions, this indicates that activity has occurred throughout the day.

The butterfly functions both as a symbol and a mechanism, transforming small physical actions into meaningful emotional signals. By shifting communication from explicit information exchange to embodied environmental feedback, the system enables presence to be perceived indirectly.

Research in mediated social touch suggests that non-verbal interaction can enhance emotional connection (van Erp & Toet, 2015), supporting this approach.

How It Works
<p align="center"> <img src="Butterfly device system layout.png" width="1000"> </p> <p align="center"> <em>Fig. 1. Butterfly device system layout</em> </p>

At Location A, a distance sensor detects proximity and maps it to wing movement speed. This data is transmitted to the paired device.

At Location B, the butterfly synchronises its motion and rotates along its wall-mounted base to represent accumulated interaction.

This combination of immediate feedback (flapping) and longer-term representation (rotation) enables both real-time and historical expressions of presence. The modular design allows multiple devices to be arranged on a wall, amplifying the overall effect.

Design Process
Hardware
<p align="center"> <img src="hardware_1.png" width="30%" /> <img src="hardware_2.png" width="30%" /> <img src="hardware_3.png" width="30%" /> </p> <p align="center"> <em>Fig. 2. Hardware</em> </p>

The system is built around the XIAO ESP32C3, providing computation and wireless communication. A VL53L0X/VL53L1X time-of-flight sensor detects presence through distance measurement. Two servos are used: an SG92R for wing flapping and an SG90-HV for rotational feedback.

The Mechanism
