System Workflow
<p align="center"> <img src="System workflow.png" width="800"> </p>

The system continuously monitors distance. When triggered, local motion is activated and a signal is sent to the paired device, which replicates the motion and rotates proportionally to interaction duration.

Development Process
Wiring and Soldering
<p align="center"> <img src="Circuit connection layout.png" width="500"> </p>

The circuit connects the sensor via I²C and controls the servos using PWM signals.

<p align="center"> <img src="Soldered circuit.jpg" width="500"> </p>
System Architecture

The system consists of embedded software on the ESP32 and a Flutter mobile app. The embedded system handles sensing, actuation, and communication, while the app manages setup and pairing.

Final Prototype
<p align="center"> <img src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/b51f80df-9aa4-479b-bb22-5021ece7eaa6" width="493"> </p>

The final prototype integrates all components within a compact enclosure.

Material testing led to the use of ripstop fabric for the wings, balancing flexibility and structural stability.

Challenges

Key challenges included:

Power management: battery limitations led to unreliable performance
Hardware integration: fragile connections increased failure risk
Communication stability: network issues affected responsiveness
Synchronisation: continuous updates increased communication load
Improvements

Future work includes:

Improved power design (battery management, low-power modes)
Better hardware integration and durability
More efficient communication and synchronisation
Enhanced interaction expressiveness
Reflections

The project demonstrates how physical computing can support new forms of remote interaction. By translating presence into motion, it offers an alternative to screen-based communication.

However, limitations highlight the gap between concept and implementation. Power constraints, mechanical limitations, and communication challenges all impacted the system’s performance.

Despite this, the project shows that small physical actions can create meaningful connections across distance.

